# Hazard Panels: A New Memory Reclamation System

## Inspiration
- Monitors (Java)
- TVAR (Haskell)
- Hazard Eras (2022)

## Problem
Traditional Hazard Pointers require manual registration.
This is error-prone and annoying.

## Solution: Hazard Panels
- One panel per CPU core
- Atomic flags (not STM)
- Automatic cleanup via lexical destructors

## How It Works
1. Each core has a panel
2. Threads use current core's panel
3. CAS operations for flags
4. No manual registration needed!

## Advantages
- Zero contention (per-core panels)
- Faster than STM (CAS only)
- Automatic (no manual work)
- Safe (flags prevent use-after-free)

## Novelty
This is a new combination of:
- Hazard Pointers (2002)
- Hazard Eras (2022)
- TVAR + Monitors (2005-2010)

## Status
- Prototype in Haskell
- Not yet tested in production
- Looking for contributors
data AtomicFlag a = AtomicFlag
    { afPtr    :: !(AtomicSmartPtr a)  
    , afStamp  :: !Word32              
    , afActive :: !(IORef Bool)         
    }
loadSmartPtr :: SmartPtr a -> IO (Maybe a)
loadSmartPtr ptr = do
    panel <- getCurrentPanel          -- Get this core's panel
    flag <- newAtomicFlag ptr panel   -- Create protection flag (CAS)
    val <- readIORef (spRef ptr)      -- Read the value (Acquire)
    clearAtomicFlag flag              -- Clear protection (Release)
    isAlive <- isPtrAlive ptr         
    return $ if isAlive then Just val else Nothing
newHazardPtr :: a -> IO (HazardPtr a)
newHazardPtr value = do
    panel <- getCurrentPanel          -- Get core's panel
    ref <- newIORef value             -- Allocate memory
    stamp <- nextStamp panel          -- Unique stamp
    let ptr = SmartPtr ref stamp panelId
    addFinalizer ptr $ retirePtr ptr  -- Auto cleanup!
    return $ HazardPtr ptr